column1: Long-term international migration: Year Ending June 2012 to Year Ending December 2024
Publication date
The data tables in this spreadsheet were originally published at 9.30am 22 May 2025
The next publication date is still to be confirmed.
Publication link
This spreadsheet is published alongside the Office for National Statistics' publication "Long-term international migration, provisional: year ending December 2024"
Provisional estimates

Estimates for Year Ending (YE) March 2024 to YE December 2024 are provisional. They are supported by assumptions that are informed by past behaviour. Small changes between time periods and estimates close to zero should be treated with caution.

The uncertainty associated with these estimates will reduce in future releases, when we have more data to confirm people’s long-term migration status.
Updates to estimates

Updates to estimates (revisions) have been made for non-EU+ nationals from YE September 2023. No updates have been made to estimates of EU+ and British nationals. 

These revisions are due to more available data, more information on Ukraine visas and improvements to how we estimate immigration and emigration of non-EU+ nationals.

EU+ is all EU countries and Norway, Iceland, Liechtenstein and Switzerland.
More information on updates to estimates is in the Long-term International Migration statistical bulletin.
Methods

Methods for estimating international migration are in development. All estimates in this spreadsheet are classified as "Official statistics in development". Our methodology and research articles contain more detail.

Data sources

Estimates of British nationals from YE September 2021 onwards are calculated based on data from the International Passenger Survey (IPS). 
Estimates for YE June 2012 to YE June 2021 are also based on IPS data but were adjusted in November 2023 using census data on population change over the decade to inform the level of immigration and emigration of British nationals over that period.

Estimates for EU+ nationals were calculated using the Registration and Population Interaction Database (RAPID) received from the Department for Work and Pensions (DWP) and His Majesty’s Revenue and Customs (HMRC).

RAPID has limited coverage of the population. To mitigate this, adjustments have been made. Additionally, the NINo registration service was partially suspended in March 2020 for certain customers, with a phased return to normal operations completed by April 2021. Some of the trends seen in EU migration from the Registration and Population Interaction Database (RAPID) may have been affected by these restrictions, where some migrants may have arrived in the UK, but were unable to register for a NINo. Therefore, they may not have been included in the estimates from RAPID.
Estimates of non-EU+ nationals were calculated using Borders and Immigration data from the Home Office.

Figures for number of visas granted are from the Home Office, figures on National Insurance number allocations are from the Department for Work and Pensions, IPS data and Census 2021 data are from Office for National Statistics.
Rounding

All estimates in the spreadsheet are individually rounded to the nearest thousand but calculations are done on unrounded numbers. As a result, rounded estimates may not sum to rounded totals and rounded net migration may not always equal rounded immigration minus rounded emigration exactly.
